article.description: Mary Fox scored a career-high 22 points, leading the Cyclones to an 81-72 victory over Baylor on Saturday night.
article.headline: Fox scores career-high 22 points for Cyclones
article.linkText: Cyclones roar back to upset No. 20 Baylor
article.story:
AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Mary Fox made sure her two brothers got the
most out of their trip to watch her play.

Fox scored a career-high 22 points and made five of Iowa State's
13 3-pointers, leading the Cyclones to an 81-72 victory over No. 18
Baylor on Saturday night.

"Last year when we played Texas her brothers were here and she
played really well in that game," Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly
said. "We've got to get her brothers here more often, I guess."

Iowa State (11-11, 4-7 Big 12) trailed by 13 midway through the
second half and was down 10 with seven minutes to go, then went on
a 16-2 run to pull ahead.

The Iowa State victory topped off a day of upsets at Hilton
Coliseum. The ISU men beat No. 11 Texas 78-77 earlier in the day.

"It was a big day for Iowa State basketball," Fennelly said.
"I haven't been this proud of a team in a long time. You've got to
have a little bit of something inside of you to keep playing and
they did."

Fox hit consecutive 3-pointers to give Iowa State a 66-64 lead
with 2:47 left and Anne O'Neil's fadeaway jumper made it 68-64.
Baylor (18-6, 6-5) had to start fouling after missing on the
ensuing possession and Iowa State made 13 of 14 free throws to wrap
it up and become the first unranked team to beat the Lady Bears
this season.

"Obviously, we win by shooting, not passing and dribbling,"
Fox said. "I was wide open. I couldn't have been more wide open.
Thankfully, I stuck it in."

Iowa State, which has struggled on offense this season, had its
highest-scoring game since an 83-52 victory over Texas Southern on
Dec. 12. Anne O'Neil added 13 points for the Cyclones, including
six straight free throws at the end. Lyndsey Medders scored 12 and
Megan Ronhovde and Katie Robinette each had 11.

Steffanie Blackmon led Baylor with 19 points and 11 rebounds,
while Jessika Stratton scored 16, all in the second half.

"We just didn't guard anybody," Baylor coach Kim
Mulkey-Robertson said. "You live and die by the 3-point shot and
they lived by it tonight."

Iowa State finished 13-for-31 on 3-pointers, with Fox going
5-for-9. Usually a spot-up jump shooter, Fox showed a new facet by
putting the ball on the floor and driving for a basket.

"That was a big play," Fennelly said. "That shocked everyone
-- them, me, her, the crowd, everybody."

Trailing by 10 late in the first half, Baylor scored the final
eight points of the half to draw to 36-34. Then, with the score
tied at 45, Baylor went on a 13-0 run that included two 3-pointers
by Stratton to go up 58-45 with 9:02 left.

The Lady Bears led 62-52 after Blackmon's baseline jumper with
7:01 remaining. But they made only one basket over the next six
minutes, and Iowa State roared back.
